{
  "text": "Tg2576 mice (an established animal model of AD) expressing the mutated human APP695 gene [CITATION_1] were obtained from Taconic (German Town, NY, USA) and were bred by mating male mice with (C57BL6/SJL) F1 females as recommended by suppliers and as described by others [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The genotyping was performed by confirming the presence of the human APP695 transgene by PCR analysis of genomic DNA in the mouse tail tips. A pair of primers for detecting human APP695 and PCR condition was as follows. Forward (59-CTGACCACTCGACCA GGTTCTGGGT-39) and reverse (59-GTGGATAACC CCTCCCCCAGCCTAGACCA -39) primers amplified a 466-bp DNA fragment. The reaction conditions used were; initial denaturation at 94uC for 10 min, 35 amplification cycles [denaturation at 94uC for 1 min, annealing at 55uC for 30 s, and elongation at 72uC for 1 min], followed by one cycle at 72uC for 5 min. Tg2576 mice over-expressing human APP695 containing the ''Swedish'' mutation have memory deficits and show progressive \u00df-amyloid plaque deposition with age [CITATION_4] . Because these mice exhibit a rapid increase in \u00df-amyloid at around 6 months after birth and the formation of amyloid plaque before 6-9 months, they represent a suitable animal model for examining relationships between \u00df-amyloid and memory [CITATION_5] .",
